4. User Experience Review
Layout: The 6-section navigation with sub-workflow tabs is well-structured. The breadcrumb + content header pattern is consistent.

Information density: Too high. The Cost & Contract section alone has 7 workflows, advanced tools expander, and multiple evidence panels. A director doesn't want to click "Load Cost Evidence" — they want it pre-loaded and summarized.

Critical UX issues:

"Load Evidence" anti-pattern — Multiple sections require the user to click a button to load data. This is a performance workaround masquerading as a feature. Users don't understand why the page is empty until they click something. The first load should be automatic; subsequent detail should be progressive.

Visual hierarchy — Based on the code, sections render with st.expander, st.columns, st.metric, and st.info/warning/error. No evidence of custom card components, KPI callout tiles, or visual severity indicators beyond Streamlit defaults. This will look like every other Streamlit app.

Chart selection — Altair is used (via _altair helper). Altair produces acceptable charts but lacks the visual polish of ECharts or Plotly for executive dashboards. Bar charts and line charts are fine; the question is whether heatmaps, treemaps, and Sankey diagrams exist where they should.

Dashboard fatigue — 167 files across 6 sections with dozens of sub-views. Nobody will use all of this. The app needs a "personalized homepage" that shows only what's relevant to the user's role today.

Mobile friendliness — Streamlit with layout="wide" is not mobile-friendly. Period. If operators need this on-call, it won't work on a phone.

Color usage — Two themes (dark/light) is fine. The company colors (ALFA green, Trexis purple, ALL blue) are defined but I see no evidence they're used consistently in charts to reinforce which data belongs to which tenant.

Charts that should be replaced:

Any "daily trend" line chart over 90 days — compress to weekly or use sparklines
Raw table dumps from ACCOUNT_USAGE — replace with ranked/sorted top-N with inline bars
