What I Genuinely Dislike
The "decision workspace" pattern is over-engineered. The command brief → evidence load → action pipeline adds cognitive overhead for users who just want to see their data. It's an architect's abstraction imposed on operators. A DBA doesn't want to "request evidence" — they want to see the failing tasks.

167 files for 6 pages is a maintenance nightmare. Cost & Contract alone has 30+ files. This codebase will be unmaintainable by anyone other than the original author within 6 months. The abstraction boundaries are too fine-grained.

The app monitors Snowflake but doesn't use Snowflake's strengths. No dynamic tables, no streams, no tasks for the mart refresh visible in the app code. The SQL setup files exist but the app itself seems to query raw ACCOUNT_USAGE at render time. This is the equivalent of building a dashboard that runs SELECT * on every page load.

It's company-specific but pretends to be general. The code is riddled with ALFA/Trexis specifics while the architecture suggests it could be multi-tenant. Pick one: either it's a bespoke ALFA tool (and simplify everything), or it's a product (and remove all ALFA references). The current middle ground is the worst of both.

No tests. 500 Python files, zero test files visible. The "contracts" system appears to be runtime assertion checking, not automated testing. This means every deploy is a prayer.
